    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{b}LUMEN THIEF - DEMOLITIONS TRAINING MANUAL (RESTRICTED):{/b}\n{i}Subject: Controlled Destruction{/i}\n{i}Instructor: Rho Sable{/i}\n{i}Trainee: Avyanna Lagrange{/i}\n{i}Summary: Making things fall is easy. Making them fall where you want is the job.{/i}\n{i}Rule 1: Know what's on the other side of the wall.{/i}\n{i}Rule 2: Precision is slower. Precision is the point.{/i}\n{i}Rule 3: The shortcut always costs more than it saves.{/i}\n{i}Addendum: If you're in a hurry, you're already losing.{/i}{{/color}}"
    pause 0.3
    narrator "{i}The range is in the cargo hold's lower section-a reinforced bay that smells like ozone and old polymer and something sharp that catches in the back of Avyanna's throat. The walls are analog-hardened against corridor drift; someone has scratched \"NO LATTICE INTERFERENCE\" into the blast door frame.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho is already there when she arrives. He's setting up a simulation grid: holographic walls projected onto a metal frame, sensors embedded in the deck to track debris patterns.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He doesn't look up.{/i}"
    rho "You're early."
    avyanna "Elisira's lesson ran short."
    rho "Elisira's lessons never run short. She let you think it did."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna blinks. He's right, probably. Everything Elisira does is deliberate.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho finishes calibrating the grid. The holographic walls flicker-gray and solid-looking, like real bulkheads. He steps back, wipes his hands on his thighs, and finally meets her eyes.{/i}"
    rho "Ready to learn how to break things?"
    avyanna "I've broken things before."
    rho "Yeah. That's not the same."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The range setup is simple: three simulated walls, each with different structural compositions displayed on a floating readout. Behind each wall, a cluster of red dots-simulated personnel. Hostiles. Civilians. Unknowns.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho hands her a pair of safety lenses. They're scratched and heavy.{/i}"
    rho "The goal isn't destruction. The goal is {i}access{/i}. You want through a wall, not through whatever's behind it."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna puts on the lenses. The world tints amber.{/i}"
    avyanna "What if what's behind it is hostile?"
    rho "Then you figure that out {i}before{/i} you blow the wall. Not after."
    narrator "{i}He taps a control. The first simulated wall highlights-standard station composite, internal bracing visible in the overlay.{/i}"
    rho "First lesson: reading structure. Every wall tells you how it wants to fall."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}He walks her through the basics.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Stress points. Load-bearing vs cosmetic. The difference between \"opens cleanly\" and \"collapses in a cascade that kills everyone in the next three rooms.\"{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna listens. Her hands itch for something to hold-a wrench, a tool, anything that makes her feel less like a student and more like someone who belongs here.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho talks with his hands. Big gestures, precise despite their size. She notices the scars on his knuckles-different from Elisira's. These are burns, not cuts. Chemical or thermal, healed rough.{/i}"
    rho "See that brace? If you hit it wrong, the whole section torques. Clean breach becomes a hull compromise."
    avyanna "And if it's an emergency? If there's no time to read the structure?"
    narrator "{i}Rho's jaw tightens. Just for a second. The grin flickers-not armor snapping into place, but armor {i}slipping{/i}. He catches it. Resets it. Too slow for casual.{/i}"
    rho "Then you're already in trouble. And trouble means people die."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}He sets up the first exercise: a simulated door, reinforced, with a lock mechanism and a timer.{/i}"
    rho "Standard Guild security door. You've got thirty seconds to get through it without triggering the alarm on the other side."
    avyanna "Thirty seconds isn't-"
    rho "Yeah. It isn't. That's the point."
    narrator "{i}He hands her a kit-small charges, placement tools, a detonator with a physical switch. No smart interface. Dumb reliability. A manifest tag on the case reads \"ALLOCATION: TRAINING-VESPER APPROVED (GRUDGINGLY).\"{/i}"
    rho "Go."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna moves. Her hands are steadier than she expected. The mine taught her to work fast, to work small, to occupy as little space and attention as possible.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She finds the hinges. Places the first charge. Too high-she adjusts. The second charge goes on the lock mechanism. The timer ticks.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She triggers the detonator.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The door simulation fractures-but wrong. The debris pattern sprays backward, toward her position. Red warning lights flash across the safety lenses.{/i}"
    rho "Dead."
    avyanna "What?"
    rho "You shaped the charge to push inward. But you didn't account for the lock's reinforcement. It redirected the blast."
    narrator "{i}He taps the control. The simulation resets.{/i}"
    rho "Try again."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}She tries again.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}And again.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The fourth attempt, the door opens cleanly. No debris spray. No alarm trigger. The red dots behind the door remain stationary-undisturbed.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's hands are shaking slightly. Not fear. Adrenaline. The shard hums at the base of her skull-warm, attentive.{/i}"
    rho "Better."
    avyanna "It took four tries."
    rho "First time I did this drill, it took me eleven."
    narrator "{i}She stares at him.{/i}"
    rho "{i}[[shrugging]]{/i} What? I'm not naturally talented. I just practice until I stop being terrible."
    narrator "{i}The honesty is disarming. Avyanna doesn't know what to do with it.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}They move to the second exercise: a wall with civilians on the other side.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The simulation shows them as blue dots-clustered, unaware, positioned where a careless breach would kill them.{/i}"
    rho "Same wall. Different problem. How do you get through without casualties?"
    avyanna "{i}[[studying the layout]]{/i} Move them first?"
    rho "Can't. They don't know you're coming. Moving them tips off the hostiles in the next section."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna frowns. The geometry is wrong. Every angle she can see puts the breach zone too close to the civilians.{/i}"
    avyanna "Then you don't go through this wall."
    narrator "{i}Rho's eyebrows lift. Interest, not approval-not yet.{/i}"
    rho "Go on."
    avyanna "You find a different entry point. One that doesn't put them at risk."
    rho "What if this is the only entry point?"
    avyanna "Then you wait. Or you change the mission parameters. Or you-"
    narrator "{i}She stops. The heat at the base of her skull pulses-frustration, maybe. The shard doesn't like constraints it can't solve.{/i}"
    avyanna "I don't know."
    rho "That's the right answer."
    narrator "{i}He taps the control. The simulation zooms out, showing the full layout-multiple entry vectors, timing windows, patrol patterns.{/i}"
    rho "There's always another way. The shortcut is the lie that says there isn't."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}They take a break. Rho produces a thermos from somewhere-coffee, or the ship's approximation of it. He pours two cups.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna takes hers. The warmth is grounding. The shard settles from frustrated to merely present.{/i}"
    rho "You're doing better than I expected."
    avyanna "{i}[[wary]]{/i} Is that a compliment?"
    rho "It's an observation. Compliments are Vesper's department."
    narrator "{i}He drinks. The silence stretches. Comfortable, almost. The range hums with residual charge.{/i}"
    avyanna "Why do you do this?"
    rho "Teach?"
    avyanna "Demolitions. Breaking things. Making them fall."
    narrator "{i}Rho's cup pauses halfway to his mouth. The grin doesn't fade, but something behind it shifts-like a door closing, then forcing itself open again.{/i}"
    rho "Because I'm good at it. And because someone has to be."
    avyanna "That's not an answer."
    rho "It's the one I've got."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The next exercise is harder.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho sets up a scenario: a hull breach in progress, structural integrity failing, hostiles on one side and crew on the other. The timer starts at sixty seconds.{/i}"
    rho "You can seal the breach with a shaped charge-collapse the corridor, buy time for evacuation. But the collapse will kill the hostiles."
    avyanna "They're hostiles. They're trying to-"
    rho "They're people. Maybe hired. Maybe coerced. Maybe desperate. Doesn't matter. They're still people."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's throat tightens.{/i}"
    avyanna "So what's the other option?"
    rho "Slower. More precise. You shape the charge differently-collapse only the section you need, leave an exit route for them. Evacuation takes longer. More risk to the crew."
    narrator "{i}He watches her. No guidance. No hints.{/i}"
    rho "Choose."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Avyanna stares at the simulation. The timer ticks. Fifty-three seconds. Fifty-two.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The shard pulses-not heat, not cold. Something else. Pressure. Like it's waiting to see what she'll do.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She thinks of the mine. Of supervisors who made choices like this every day. \"Acceptable losses.\" \"Necessary sacrifices.\" Words that meant: {i}someone else pays so I don't have to.{/i}"
    narrator "In the Kennel, I was the acceptable loss. I was the necessary sacrifice. I will not be the one who decides someone else is."
    avyanna "The slower way."
    rho "Even with the risk?"
    avyanna "Even with the risk."
    narrator "{i}Rho nods. His face is unreadable.{/i}"
    rho "Do it."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}She fails the first attempt. The collapse is too wide-one of the blue dots winks out. Civilian casualty.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She fails the second attempt. The breach isn't sealed in time. The timer hits zero.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The third attempt, she gets it right. The hostiles escape through their exit route. The crew evacuates. The breach holds.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's hands are shaking again. Not adrenaline this time. Something else.{/i}"
    rho "Slower is harder. Slower takes practice. But slower is what we do."
    avyanna "Why?"
    narrator "{i}The question comes out sharper than she intended. The shard's pressure hasn't faded-it's watching, listening, {i}waiting.{/i}"
    avyanna "Why does it matter? If they're hostile-if they're trying to kill us-why does it matter if they have an exit?"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Rho is quiet for a long moment. The range hums. Somewhere in the ship, a ventilation system cycles.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}When he speaks, the humor is gone. His voice is flat, careful, like he's reciting something he's said before-to himself, in the dark, when no one else was listening.{/i}"
    rho "Because shortcuts have a cost. And the cost is never the one you expect."
    avyanna "That's not-"
    rho "I killed thirty-seven people with a shortcut."
    narrator "{i}The words land like a physical weight. Avyanna's mouth closes.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho doesn't look at her. He's looking at the simulation grid-at the blue dots, the red dots, the debris patterns that mark where walls used to be.{/i}"
    rho "I was Compact military. Then rim. Then mercenary. Whatever paid, wherever the work was. I was good at it. Fast. Efficient."
    narrator "{i}His hands curl around the thermos. The metal creaks.{/i}"
    rho "There was a situation. Andros Station. Under siege. Hostages in one section, hostiles in another. Command said we had a window-forty seconds to breach, extract, and evac before the station's core went critical."
    avyanna "{i}[[quiet]]{/i} What happened?"
    rho "I took the shortcut. Shaped charge through the main corridor. Fast. Clean. The hostiles went down. The window held."
    narrator "{i}A beat.{/i}"
    rho "Except the corridor connected to a secondary habitation module. Civilians. Families. The shockwave killed them before they knew we were there."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's chest tightens. The shard goes cold-not pain, but something like recognition. Like it knows this shape of grief.{/i}"
    rho "Thirty-seven people. Twelve of them were children."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The silence stretches. The range's ambient hum fills the space between them.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna doesn't know what to say. In the mine, people died all the time. You learned not to look. Not to count. Not to carry the weight of faces you couldn't save.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}But Rho carries them. She can see it now-in the set of his shoulders, the tightness around his eyes, the way his jokes deflect before anyone can ask.{/i}"
    avyanna "The crew knows?"
    rho "Elia knows. Elisira figured it out. Vesper has access to records she shouldn't. Jalen... Jalen lost people too. Different way. Same weight."
    avyanna "And they still-"
    rho "They still trust me."
    narrator "{i}He says it like he doesn't understand it. Like every day he wakes up expecting them to finally realize what he is.{/i}"
    rho "Elia gave me a rule. {i}Precision is the only absolution.{/i} She didn't forgive me. She just... kept trusting me anyway. Made me earn it."
    narrator "{i}He looks at Avyanna. Really looks-not the casual assessment of a teacher, but something rawer. Someone deciding how much of themselves to show.{/i}"
    rho "That's why we choose the slower way. That's why shortcuts cost more than they save. Because the people behind those walls-the blue dots, the red dots, whoever they are-they're not numbers. They're faces you'll carry forever."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's throat is tight. The heat at the base of her skull has shifted-not cold anymore, but not warm either. Present. Witnessing.{/i}"
    avyanna "I'm sorry."
    rho "{i}[[shaking his head]]{/i} Don't be. Just... remember."
    avyanna "Remember what?"
    rho "That the shortcut always lies. It says it's faster. It says it's cleaner. It says the cost is acceptable."
    narrator "{i}He sets down the thermos. His hands are steady again-the mask reassembling, the armor clicking back into place.{/i}"
    rho "The cost is never acceptable. It's just the one you haven't paid yet."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}They run through two more exercises. Avyanna's focus is sharper now-not just technical, but moral. She reads the simulations differently. The blue dots aren't abstractions anymore. They're faces she hasn't met yet.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Rho's teaching shifts too. Less joking. More direct. He points out her mistakes without softening them, but he also names what she's doing right.{/i}"
    rho "Good. You're thinking about the exit before you think about the entry."
    avyanna "You said there's always another way."
    rho "There is. The trick is being patient enough to find it."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}At the end of the session, Rho packs up the simulation grid. The cargo hold returns to its default state-crates, cargo nets, the quiet hum of environmental systems.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna helps without being asked. The work is familiar-lifting, stacking, fitting pieces into spaces where they belong. The mine taught her this much.{/i}"
    rho "Same time tomorrow?"
    avyanna "If you want."
    rho "I want."
    narrator "{i}He pauses, one hand on a crate.{/i}"
    rho "Avyanna."
    narrator "{i}She looks up.{/i}"
    rho "You asked why I do this. Breaking things. Making them fall."
    narrator "{i}His voice is lighter now-the armor back, the jokes hovering at the edge. But underneath, something true.{/i}"
    rho "I do it because I already know what happens when you do it wrong. And I'd rather teach someone to do it right than watch them learn the way I did."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Later, in the corridor outside the cargo hold, Avyanna pauses.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The shard hums-low, steady. Not pain. Not pressure. Just... presence. Acknowledgment.{/i}"
    narrator "He carries thirty-seven faces."
    narrator "{i}The thought settles into her like a new weight. Not crushing. Just there.{/i}"
    narrator "I carry the Kennel. He carries the corridor. Jalen carries Kettering's Rest. Everyone on this ship carries something."
    narrator "{i}She thinks of Elia's rule: {i}Precision is the only absolution.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}It doesn't sound like forgiveness. It sounds like a job. Something you do every day, whether you feel like it or not. A discipline instead of a pardon.{/i}"
    narrator "Maybe that's what floors are. Not absolution. Just... the work that makes you worth trusting."
    narrator "{i}The heat along her spine spreads-warmer now. Agreement, maybe. Or just the shard learning alongside her.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna walks back toward her bunk. The ship hums. Somewhere ahead, someone is arguing about the coffee machine again.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She almost smiles.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<WAFFLE.BAT// OBSERVATION: trainee completed demolitions drill | INFERENCE: moral framework strengthening | CONFIDENCE: 0.81 | NOTE: slower is harder. slower is what we do.>{{/color}}"

