label act1_16_breach_hymn_coda_0:
    narrator "{i}— Rho's Ledger —{/i}"
    pause 0.5
    narrator "{i}0300. The cargo hold is empty. The simulation grid is packed away. The deck plates are cold under Rho's boots.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He sits on a crate in the dark, datapad in hand. The screen's glow is the only light-blue and clinical, washing out the color in his face.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The file is encrypted. Three layers. Cinnamon could break it-she's broken harder-but she won't. Trust boundary. Some doors stay closed because someone asks, not because they're locked.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}{b}LEDGER - PERSONAL - RHO SABLE{/b}{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The entries are names.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Thirty-seven of them at the top. Andros Station. The corridor. The shortcut that wasn't.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Below that: others. People who died because he was fast instead of careful. People who died because he followed orders. People who died because he was young and stupid and believed that \"acceptable losses\" was a real thing.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He doesn't read the names. He knows them. They're carved into the back of his skull, behind his eyes, in the place where dreams should be.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Tonight, he adds a new entry. Not a name. A number.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}{b}Days since last shortcut: 847{/b}{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He stares at it. The number feels fragile. Tomorrow it will be 848. Then 849. Then a thousand, maybe. Or zero, if he screws up.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The jokes are armor. Everyone knows that. Rho knows they know. It doesn't matter. The armor works because it gives people something to react to-something easier than the truth.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The truth is this: the ledger is discipline. The count is work. Every day he doesn't take the shortcut is a floor under someone else's feet.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Precision is the only absolution.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He'd laughed when she said it. A short, bitter sound. \"I'm not looking for absolution,\" he'd told her.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}And Elia-small and calm and carrying her own weight of faces-had just looked at him.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}\"Then what are you looking for?\"{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He still doesn't have an answer. But he has the ledger. He has the count. He has tomorrow, and the day after, and every day after that where he doesn't take the shortcut.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}That's not absolution. That's not forgiveness. That's just... staying alive long enough to do the work.{/i}"
    pause 0.3
    narrator "{i}Rho closes the datapad. The cargo hold goes dark.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Somewhere in the ship, someone laughs. Jalen, probably-or Nyx, if they're feeling bold. The sound is muffled, distant, real.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}He sits with it for a moment. The laughter. The hum of the ship. The weight of the faces he carries.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Then he stands. Rolls his shoulders. Lets the grin slide back into place like a familiar mask.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Tomorrow, he teaches Avyanna how to make a wall fall without hurting anyone behind it. Tomorrow, the count goes to 848.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Tonight, he adds the new number to the ledger and doesn't sleep.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The next morning, Avyanna finds Rho in the galley with Cinnamon's interface open on a datapad.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Numbers scroll across the screen-percentages, curves, compound functions that make her head hurt.{/i}"
    avyanna "{i}[[cautious]]{/i} What's that."
    rho "{i}[[not looking up]]{/i} Math."
    avyanna "I know that. What kind."
    rho "The kind that keeps people enslaved."
    narrator "{i}He taps the screen. A debt contract fills the display-dense legalese wrapped around a single interest rate.{/i}"
    rho "You know what this number means?"
    avyanna "{i}[[reading]]{/i} Twenty-two percent annual interest."
    rho "No."
    narrator "{i}He looks at her. The mask-grin is gone.{/i}"
    rho "It means they never intended you to pay it off."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna's stomach drops.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<CINNAMON.EXE// DEMONSTRATION AVAILABLE: compound interest visualization | RECOMMEND: show her the curve>{{/color}}"
    narrator "{i}The screen shifts. A graph appears-a line that starts flat, then curves upward like a scream.{/i}"
    rho "This is what twenty-two percent does over time. Every year, you owe more. Every payment you make barely touches the principal."
    avyanna "But if I just work harder-"
    rho "No."
    narrator "{i}He says it flat. Final.{/i}"
    rho "You can't outwork compound interest. That's the point. They built the math to be unbeatable."
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<CINNAMON.EXE// CALCULATION: at 22%% annual interest, original debt of 50k credits | TIME TO DOUBLE: 3.5 years | TIME TO QUADRUPLE: 7 years | ASSUMING MINIMUM PAYMENTS: never resolves>{{/color}}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna reads the numbers. Her hands go cold.{/i}"
    avyanna "{i}[[quiet]]{/i} I would have died there."
    rho "Yes."
    rho "Or your kids would've. Or their kids. That's the design."
    narrator "{i}He swipes to a different screen-a cleaner contract, different numbers.{/i}"
    rho "This is what non-predatory lending looks like. Five percent. Fixed term. No compound interest on missed payments."
    rho "The math doesn't trap you. It just... exists."
    avyanna "The mine didn't teach us about interest rates."
    rho "Of course they didn't. If you understood the math, you'd understand you were being robbed."
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<CINNAMON.EXE// PHILOSOPHY: innumeracy is a control tool | OBSERVATION: people who can't calculate percentages can't argue with debt claims | STRATEGY: teach the math, break the control>{{/color}}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna stares at the graphs.{/i}"
    avyanna "So if someone won't show me the math..."
    rho "They're lying."
    rho "Or they're too embarrassed to admit they don't understand it either."
    narrator "{i}He pulls up another screen-shaped charge calculations, blast radius formulas, safety margins.{/i}"
    rho "This is how I plan breaches. Math. Precision. I can't afford to guess."
    rho "If I get the angle wrong by five degrees, the blast goes through the wall and kills someone behind it."
    rho "If I get the compound wrong by ten percent, the charge doesn't breach at all and we're trapped."
    narrator "{i}He looks at her.{/i}"
    rho "Numbers don't lie. They don't care about your story. They just... are."
    rho "That's why they're powerful. And that's why people who want to control you make sure you never learn them."
    avyanna "{i}[[slow, tasting it]]{/i} So learning math is..."
    rho "Leverage."
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<CINNAMON.EXE// LESSON PLAN AVAILABLE: basic percentages, compound interest, probability, statistical literacy | ESTIMATED TIME: 6 hours distributed | OUTCOME: quantitative ammunition against exploitation>{{/color}}"
    avyanna "Cinnamon wants to teach me."
    rho "Good. Let her."
    rho "Percentages first. Then compound interest. Then probability-so you know when someone's selling you a bad bet."
    avyanna "And then I can..."
    rho "Argue. Prove. Calculate your own risk instead of trusting theirs."
    narrator "{i}He closes the datapad.{/i}"
    rho "They kept you innumerate for a reason. We're fixing that."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna feels something shift. Like a lock she didn't know existed just... opened.{/i}"
    avyanna "{i}[[quiet]]{/i} Thank you."
    rho "{i}[[grin sliding back]]{/i} Don't thank me yet. Cinnamon's a brutal teacher. She'll make you show your work."
    narrator "{{color=#43d4a8}}<CINNAMON.EXE// AFFIRMATIVE: precision is required | NO SHORTCUTS | UNDERSTANDING > MEMORIZATION>{{/color}}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna almost laughs. Almost.{/i}"
    avyanna "I think I can handle that."
    rho "Good."
    narrator "{i}He stands, stretches, lets the dad-joke energy return like a comfortable coat.{/i}"
    rho "Now go eat breakfast. Can't learn math on an empty stomach. That's just bad engineering."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna watches him go. The datapad stays on the table, numbers still scrolling.{/i}"
